etymologies: Old English theg(e)n ‘servant, soldier’, of Germanic origin; related to German Degen ‘warrior’, from an Indo-European root shared by Greek teknon ‘child’, tokeus ‘parent’

definitions: (in Anglo-Saxon England) a man who held land granted by the king or by a military nobleman, ranking between an ordinary freeman and a hereditary noble.
shortDefinitions: (in Anglo-Saxon England) man who held land granted by king or by military nobleman, ranking between ordinary freeman and hereditary noble

definitions: (in Scotland) a man, often the chief of a clan, who held land from a Scottish king and ranked with an earl's son
shortDefinitions: (in Scotland) man who held land from Scottish king
